SAIL. In insurance law. To put to sea;
to begin a voyage. The least locomotion,
with readiness of equipment and clearance,
satisfies a warranty to sail. Pittegrew v.
Pringle, 3 Barn. & Adol. 514. ;

SCAPHA. Lat. In Roman law.
a lighter. A ship’s boat.


A boat;

SIGNATORIUS ANNULUS.
In the civil law. A signet-ring;
Dig. 50, 16, 74.

SOC, SOK, or SOKA. In Saxon law.
Jurisdiction; a power or privilege to administer justice and execute the laws; also a
shire, circuit, or territory. Cowell. ;

SOLDIER. A military man;
in the army.


a private

SPITAL, or SPITTLE. A charitable
foundation; a hospital for diseased people;
a hospital. Cowell.

SURDUS. Lat. In the civil law. Deaf;
a deaf person. Inst. 2, 12, 3. Surdus et
mutus, a deaf and dumb person.

SUSPEND. To interrupt; to cause to
cease for a time; to stay, delay, or hinder ;
to discontinue temporarily, but with an expectation or purpose of resumption. To forbid a public officer, attorney, or ecclesiastical
person from performing his duties or exercising his functions for a more or less definite
interval of time. See Insurance Co. v. Aiken,
82 Va. 428; Stack v. O’Hara, 98 Pa. 232;
Reside v. U. S., 8 Wall. 42, 19 L. Ed. 318;
Williston v. Camp, 9 Mont. 88, 22 Pac. 501;
Dyer v. Dyer, 17 R. I. 547, 23 Atl. 910; State
v. Melvin, 166 Mo. 565, 66 S. W. 534; Poe
